\begin_layout Subsection*
The Matrix of a Linear Transformation
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
matrix!standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

|(
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose a map 
\begin_inset Formula $G:\mathbb{R}^{n}\times\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\mathbf{v})=M\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 for some matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Then, by theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:matrixproperties-part1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 part 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thmpart:left-distributive"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $G(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v})=M(\mathbf{u}+\mathbf{v})=M\mathbf{u}+M\mathbf{v}=G(\mathbf{u})+G(\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 and by theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:matrixproperties-part2"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 part 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thmpart:ass-scalar-mult-2-matrices"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $G(c\mathbf{u})=M(c\mathbf{u})=c(M\mathbf{u})=cG(\mathbf{u})$
\end_inset

 for any vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{u}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 and any scalar 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 is a linear transformation.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose a linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is given by matrix multiplication by an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 That is, 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{v})=A\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 Then it is easy to calculate its action on the vectors 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
0\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{array}\right],\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
1\\
0\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{array}\right],\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\\
1\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{array}\right],\ldots,\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\\
0\\
\vdots\\
1
\end{array}\right],
\]

\end_inset

the columns of the 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 identity matrix.
 Thinking of matrix multiplication of a vector as a linear combination of
 the columns of the matrix, it is clear that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
A\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
0\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{array}\right]=A_{:,1},\ A\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
1\\
0\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{array}\right]=A_{:,2},\ A\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\\
1\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{array}\right]=A_{:,3},\ldots,A\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\\
0\\
\vdots\\
1
\end{array}\right]=A_{:,n}.
\]

\end_inset

In short, 
\begin_inset Formula $AI_{:,j}=A_{:,j}$
\end_inset

.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 column of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 is the image of the 
\begin_inset Formula $j^{th}$
\end_inset

 column of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
On the other hand, suppose you know the images of the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 but are not given 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 as a matrix product.
 All you know is 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
T(I_{:,1})=\mathbf{c}_{1},\ T(I_{:,2})=\mathbf{c}_{2},\ldots,T(I_{:,n})=\mathbf{c}_{n}
\]

\end_inset

for some 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times1$
\end_inset

 vectors 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{c}_{1},\mathbf{c}_{2},\ldots,\mathbf{c}_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 It turns out this is enough information to determine 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 can be represented by matrix multiplication! Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbf{v}=\left[\begin{array}{c}
v_{1}\\
v_{2}\\
\vdots\\
v_{n}
\end{array}\right]$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times1$
\end_inset

 vector.
 Due to linearity,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T(\mathbf{v}) & =T\left(\left[\begin{array}{c}
v_{1}\\
v_{2}\\
\vdots\\
v_{n}
\end{array}\right]\right)\\
 & =T\left(\left[\begin{array}{c}
v_{1}\\
0\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{array}\right]+\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
v_{2}\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{array}\right]+\cdots+\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\\
\vdots\\
v_{n}
\end{array}\right]\right)
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
 & =T\left(v_{1}\left[\begin{array}{c}
1\\
0\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{array}\right]+v_{2}\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
1\\
\vdots\\
0
\end{array}\right]+\cdots+v_{n}\left[\begin{array}{c}
0\\
0\\
\vdots\\
1
\end{array}\right]\right)\\
 & =T\left(v_{1}I_{:,1}+v_{2}I_{:,2}+\cdots+v_{n}I_{:,n}\right)\\
 & =T\left(v_{1}I_{:,1}\right)+T\left(v_{2}I_{:,2}\right)+\cdots+T\left(v_{n}I_{:,n}\right)\\
 & =v_{1}T\left(I_{:,1}\right)+v_{2}T\left(I_{:,2}\right)+\cdots+v_{n}T\left(I_{:,n}\right)\\
 & =v_{1}\mathbf{c}_{1}+v_{2}\mathbf{c}_{2}+\cdots+v_{n}\mathbf{c}_{n}\\
 & =\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\mathbf{c}_{1} & \mathbf{c}_{2} & \cdots & \mathbf{c}_{n}\end{array}\right]\left[\begin{array}{c}
v_{1}\\
v_{2}\\
\vdots\\
v_{n}
\end{array}\right]\\
 & =\left[\begin{array}{cccc}
\mathbf{c}_{1} & \mathbf{c}_{2} & \cdots & \mathbf{c}_{n}\end{array}\right]\mathbf{v}.
\end{align*}

\end_inset

In other words, to represent 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 as a matrix product, form the matrix with columns equal to the images of
 the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These calculations justify the folowing theorem.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem

\series bold
\shape up
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "thm:Standard-Matrix"

\end_inset

[The Standard Matrix of a Linear Transformation]
\series default
\shape default
 
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
matrix!standard|textidxthm
\end_layout

\end_inset

Given a transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $T:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

 is linear if and only if 
\begin_inset Formula $T(\mathbf{v})=M\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{:j}=T(I_{:,j}),\,j=1,2,\ldots,n$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is called the standard matrix of 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\noindent
\begin_inset Index idx
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
matrix!standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

|)
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset

In words, a transformation from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 is linear if and only if it can be represented by multiplication by a matrix
 whose columns are the images of the columns of the identity matrix.
\end_layout

