\begin_layout Standard
As we have seen previously, any invertible matrix can be written as a product
 of elementary matrices.
 If there were some connection between matrix multiplication and linear
 transformations, we would be on our way to a comprehensive characterization
 of linear transformations from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

.
 By theorem 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thm:matrixproperties-part1"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 part 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "thmpart:associativity-multiplication"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $A(B\mathbf{v})=(AB)\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
 In terms of linear transformations, the left side, 
\begin_inset Formula $A(B\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

, represents applying the transformation whose associated matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 first and then applying the transformation whose associated matrix is 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 to the result.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $A(B\mathbf{v})$
\end_inset

 represents composing the two transformations whose associated matrices
 are 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 The right side, 
\begin_inset Formula $(AB)\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, represents applying the transformation whose associated matrix is the
 product 
\begin_inset Formula $AB$
\end_inset

.
 It must be that matrix multiplication corresponds to function composition!
 To facilitate the following discussion, which puts these words into symbols
 and elaborates, for any matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 we adopt the notation 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{M}$
\end_inset

 for the linear transformation 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{M}:\mathbb{R}^{n}\to\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{M}(\mathbf{v})=M\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{A}$
\end_inset

 be an arbitrary linear transformation from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{m}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{B}$
\end_inset

 an arbitrary linear transformation from 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{p}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{n}$
\end_inset

, the following calculation encapsulates the idea that matrix multiplication
 corresponds to function composition.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
(T_{A}\circ T_{B})(\mathbf{v}) & =T_{A}(T_{B}(\mathbf{v}))\\
 & =T_{A}(B\mathbf{v})\\
 & =A(B\mathbf{v})\\
 & =(AB)\mathbf{v}\\
 & =T_{AB}(\mathbf{v}).
\end{align*}

\end_inset

This calculation has two important consequences.
 First, if 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is invertible, then 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{M}\circ T_{M^{-1}}=T_{M^{-1}}\circ T_{M}=T_{I}$
\end_inset

.
 In other words, 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(T_{M}\circ T_{M^{-1}}\right)(\mathbf{v})=\left(T_{M^{-1}}\circ T_{M}\right)(\mathbf{v})=T_{I}(\mathbf{v})=I\mathbf{v}=\mathbf{v}$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{M}$
\end_inset

 is invertible and 
\begin_inset Formula $(T_{M})^{-1}=T_{M^{-1}}$
\end_inset

.
 Second, if 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is invertible and we write 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 as the product of elementary matrices, 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{1}E_{2}\cdots E_{p}$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
T_{M}(\mathbf{v}) & =M\mathbf{v}\\
 & =(E_{1}E_{2}\cdots E_{p})\mathbf{v}\\
 & =\left(T_{E_{1}}\circ T_{E_{2}}\circ\cdots\circ T_{E_{p}}\right)(\mathbf{v}),
\end{align*}

\end_inset

so 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{M}$
\end_inset

 is a composition of linear transformations whose associated matrices are
 elementary matrices.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Finally, because the action of transformations defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 elementary matrices include only reflection, scaling, and shearing, these
 actions and compositions of them are the only actions of invertible linear
 transformations on 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So what about 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{M}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is noninvertible? Noninvertible matrices have linearly dependent columns
 and linearly dependent rows.
 In the case of 
\begin_inset Formula $2\times2$
\end_inset

 matrices that means the rows are multiples of one another or one of the
 rows contains two zeros.
 Likewise, either its columns are multiples of one another or one of the
 columns contains two zeros.
 In any case, it has the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
N=\left[\begin{array}{cc}
ka & \ell a\\
kb & \ell b
\end{array}\right]
\]

\end_inset

for some scalars 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b,k,\ell$
\end_inset

.
 Can you verify this form covers all four cases? Answer on page 
